segments.text: ABC.
Testing, testing, one, two, three, one, two, three.
This is Thursday, May 25th, or 6th.
Haskell, I think it's the 23rd, isn't it?
I don't know.
Yeah, it's the 23rd.
Anyway, we're in Austin, and I have the pleasure and honor of interviewing Hector Gutierrez.
Hector, to introduce yourself to this tape and anyone who might...
read the typed version, describe your biography before you came to A&M.
Family, where, when, where'd you go to high school and all that?
I grew up in a family of five children.
I was the oldest child.
Considered my family working class, middle class family.
Went to high school at Martin High School, which is the only high school in Laredo, until my senior year, which is when we built our second high school.
That high school was named J.W.
Nixon.
after the superintendent of schools and we were the first graduating class of Nixon.
How many in your class?
We had about 600 people in my class.
I was elected student body president my senior year and I was also head of the ROTC and had the privilege of
of receiving the valedictory honors at the end of my senior year.
What did your family do for income?
My father was a car salesman.
My mother was a GS-6 at the Air Force Base, so they were both working parents.
I might say that my grandfather
Teodosio was one of the leaders of, I guess, in the business movement in Laredo that involved, what I would say, Hispanics.
Even Laredo, which is 95% Hispanic, didn't have really any leaders that the community saw as business leaders, and Teodosio was in that category.
When he died, he was probably, I'd say, in the top 10 of wealth in Laredo.
So my father grew up in a very wealthy family.
The house where they lived is a historic home.
It's a mansion.
His sister still lives in that house.
And so my father came from a lot of wealth, but my grandfather died very young.
And as a result of that early death at age 49,
My father and his brothers weren't able to manage the money.
They had cotton gins.
They had a lot of the land where Tony Sanchez has discovered his oil and gas was my grandfather's land, but they sold the mineral rights.
When did your family get to the Laredo area?
My grandfather came to Texas from Guerrero, which is where Lake Falcon is.
He crossed
border when he was seven years old with the current mayor's, mayor of Austin's father, Gus Garcia.
Gus Garcia's dad and my grandfather crossed at the same time and Zapata and that was when he was six and he died when he was 49.
So it was, you know, the early 1900s, late 1800s.
Okay.
Why did you go to A&M?
I always wanted to be an Aggie.
Well, first of all, I felt always that I was going to serve my country somehow, that I was going to have to go into the military somehow.
Excuse me one second.
I'm getting up paid.
Why you attended A&M?
Where did you hear about it, and what had you heard about it?

Well, I, this is a very, I remember going to a family's home, and on their mantle were pictures of these two young men in uniform, and I asked, it was my younger brother's godparents, and it was Gus and Lua Fernandez.
And one of the pictures on the mantle was Raul Fernandez, and it was when he was at A&M.
And I always asked, why is he in uniform?
And these godparents of my younger brother would tell me about A&M.
And this handsome, sharp young man and his brother, I don't know whether his brother was in an army uniform or whether he was an Aggie as well, but that influenced me.
And I figured, you know, there were other families that I knew had children that had gone to A&M.
And I figured if I went into the military, I wanted to be an officer.
And I, of course, I was an ROTC in high school.
These were, you know, the late 60s, and, you know, we had the Cuban Missile Crisis, we had the Cold War, we had, you know, the aftermath of the Korean War, and we had Vietnam.
I felt if I was going to serve my country, I wanted to be an officer and go to a school that afforded me the opportunity to...
But no older brother or first cousin?
Nobody.
In fact, all of my family, all my cousins, all my brothers and sisters are all Longhorns.
I'm the only Aggie in the family.
All right.
Now, among your siblings, you're which one?
I'm the oldest.
You're the oldest.
So, all right.
So, you're, are you the first in your family tree to go to college?
Yes.
Mom and dad didn't?
My mother and father did not.
Now, my brother had, I mean, my father had two brothers that went to Wharton.
So, so that, that tells you a little bit about the family he came from and...
Did you understand growing up that you were going to go to college?
Definitely.
How can they do that?
I knew it would be hard because I knew that I would have to probably work to get myself through college.
I worked summers at Sears during high school, but my father, on his selling car salaries, put me through college.
I didn't have to work through college.
When did you first visit A&M and what was your impression of it?
The first time I visited A&M was the day I was dropped off.
Oh, really?
And had my trunk in
Did A&M do anything to recruit you?
No.
You applied.
I applied and I think another influencer for me was that a lot of my friends that were going to college and, you know, I was pretty studious but I was also active in extracurricular activities.
A lot of the kids that were going to college from Nixon, that first graduating class,
happened to be going to A&M, and so we all went to A&M together.
And when we started applying, we applied together, and we compared letters of acceptance with each other.
And I believe you said before we turned the machine on of your high school record, summarize that.
I think in my high school class,
I was very active always politically with student council and was either in junior high I was president of student council and senior high school I was president of student council.
I was also head of the ROTC.
I don't know whether I stated it while I was on record or not, but the valedictorian was... Did you get a little scholarship as a...
I got, I think, about a $1,000 scholarship, which was a lot back then.
Oh, yeah.
And I was also the most popular boy.
So I wasn't totally a nerd by being valedictorian.
I was most popular as well.
Right.
So when you went up to A&M to enroll in the fall of 1968.
No, the fall of 65.
It was the first year that the Corps was non-compulsory.
How did you get there?
When you went up there, who took you?
I went with a friend of mine.
My parents didn't take me up there.
I went with a friend who had a car.
And what did you take in that, what stuff?

You know, the main thing I took, I took a couple of, I remember I took some books, I took obviously casual clothes, my mother's cookies, some, I remember I put a lot of salsa, cans of salsa in my footlocker.
But I got there not knowing what outfit I was going to be in.
what dorm I was going to be in.
And the first night, there were five Aggies that arrived.
And five of us went up in the car, and how we got that stuff in the car, I don't know.

But we were all afraid to spend the night in our own room, so we decided that we'd go stay with an individual by the name of Doug Kennedy, who happened to be in the jock dorm, and those dorms were air-conditioned.
Ours were not.
So five young men...
stayed in the same room on two beds, one on the floor, two of us on each of the single beds, you know.
Was this in Henderson Hall?
Yes, it was Henderson Hall.
All right.
Exactly.
Then you go back.
How were you received?
Well, Haskell, I'll tell a funny story that I got to my outfit.
I was in Squadron 9, and there was an individual by the name of Chapeau was his last name.
He was a senior.

He was our commander, and I never thought I'd forget his first name, but at this moment, I'm having trouble recollecting his first name, but he was from San Francisco, and he was taking aerospace engineering, and
He introduced himself to me.
He was in his senior boots and I was carrying a footlocker and he asked me if I knew how to whip out.
And I looked at him and I said, of course I do.
He said, well, do it.

and i was with a bunch of friends and he was with a bunch of seniors and i said not here i obviously did not know what whipping out was and it had a different connotation with me than it had with him but i of course everybody started laughing and
I'm sort of embarrassed telling that story, but that was my first introduction.
He asked me if I knew how to whip out, and I said, of course, but not in the hallway and not in the presence of other people.
Did he give you any kind of lecture or anything?
He showed me how to whip out.
Oh, okay.
He said, let me show you how to whip out, and at that point, I started backing away and...

He put out his hand, and he stated his name, and he told me where he was from, and he said, my name is Chapo, I'm from San Francisco, and I'm taking aerospace engineering, and your name is Gutierrez, and you're from Laredo, and you're taking mathematics.
And he said, that's whipping out.
And so...
Do you have any idea how you got assigned to the unit you got assigned?
No idea.
I knew I was going to be in an Air Force unit and at that time there were no, you couldn't lobby to be in certain units like you do now.
In fact, it was all random.
You didn't know how you were picked or how you were selected to go into certain units.
All right, describe then you and your new roommate moving into your quarters.
My first roommate was Michael Yodite, who was J-O-D-E-I-T, Michael, and he was from Houston, Texas, and he was sort of, you know, about a foot and a half taller than I was.
He had probably never met a Hispanic in his life, and we were rooming together, and we became the best of friends, and... How quickly?
Very quickly, but at the end of my, at the end of his first semester, he ended up going to room with another person, then I had a second roommate whose name was Frank Davis.
He was also from, from the Houston area.
Describe what y'all had in that room that fall.
Describe the furnishings.
The main thing we had was two desks, two beds, a bunk bed.
Who slept up and who down?
I slept up and he slept down.
Why?
He slept because he was so tall he was afraid his feet would hang out too.
I told him, I said, Michael, your feet will hang out on the first bunk too, but he was so tall that he thought that
that it'd be better for the short guy to be on top, and it was more hassle.
Did you have any radio typewriter or anything like that?
I had a radio.
I wasn't able to have a record player, and it was a turntable record player, until my sophomore year.
Very Spartan.
We had a sink in our room and, you know, learned how to put together uniform and learn how to shine shoes pretty quickly.
Who gave you any, you and your buddies who were fish, who gave y'all the training about Aggie traditions and how to do and not to do things in the dorm?
The main training came from, quite frankly, the sophomores.
We didn't, I mean, prior to my going to A&M, I had no mentor prior to my going to A&M that told me what it was like or that even gave me a clue of what it was like.
When I was in high school, I concentrated on high school.
I was totally consuming, and I didn't have any idea of what A&M looked like.
where the dorms were, the kind of training we would have, how ROTC at Texas A&M would greatly differ from that which we got, you know, as a course study in a high school.
So it was a world unknown to me.
I did not realize
how competitive everything would be.
Even though we were a freshman class, within the class there was competition.
Competition, in my opinion, to be the best drilled, to be the best educated freshman.
Did your outfit have a nickname?
Hellcat 9.
Hellcat 9.
And did a motto or anything like that?
I don't recall a motto, but we were known, you know, Hellcat 9 was known as, you know, a bunch of hell raisers.
And it was also the outfit in the Air Force that was known for hazing more than any other Air Force outfit.
How soon did you get hazed?
You had to sign hazing however you want to.
I define hazing as, in the very loose sense of the word, hazing to me was having to do push-ups, having to do sit-ups, having to do chores for the upperclassmen like shine their shoes.
And that began, all that began when?
The very first hour that I was there.
it kept me in shape.
I'd never been in better shape in all my life.
Hazing to me was running.
It wasn't, it wasn't defined in my mind at that point as acts of demoralizing a human being or demonizing a person.
I never got hit by a board, but I never,
I never was hit by a board.
I did a lot of pushups, I did a lot of sit-ups, and I did a lot of running for the mistakes that I made.
Were there cush questions in the chow hall?
Yes.
Do you remember any of, do you have any favorite cush questions?

know, ask, there are certain things in my life that I remember vividly, but the Cush questions were, I mean, obviously, you know, they'd ask us campusology, and we had, you know, we had, we had to answer questions correctly, and... All right, let me share it with you, my favorite one that I've learned, and you can use this perhaps in some of your service activities at that big dome building.
How many stars are there in the Texas flag?
No, there's two.
There's one on each side.
And if they say two, you say, no, there's one.
It goes through both ways.
You can't win.
That's right.
That's right.
In other words, the upperclassmen would get the kush no matter what.
That's right.
In the dining hall lingo, what were some of your favorite food nicknames?
Well, to me, it was the bull neck was meat, and of course spuds were the potatoes, and buckshot were peas.
You know, the cow was milk, and I don't remember what water was.
Was tea horse?
Because wasn't it, it was some animal, wasn't it?
Tea was, I don't know whether tea was horse or not, but I know that... What was ice cream?
I don't know that one.
And all desserts were cush?
All desserts were cush.
There was no...
Bread was deal?
Deal.
Let's see.
Mustard was baby?
Mustard was baby.
And I won't repeat what mayonnaise was.
Yeah, yeah, yeah.
The...
How soon was it before the upperclassmen whipped you fish into training, where you fell in, you marched, you did this, that, and the other?
The first week.
I mean, they, you know, I didn't know anything.
Well, I knew a lot about marching because I was in ROTC, and I was head of the ROTC, and so I was
pretty good at marching.
But I tell you Haskell, I didn't want to show that off because you didn't want to stand out too much too quickly, okay?
And so I learned to march with everybody else.
I didn't want to display the fact that I was a Nazi.
And in your era,
Did the fall semester begin in late September?
It began in mid-September.
Mid-September.
Mid-September.
And we went after Christmas to finish the semester.
That is correct.
That is correct.
Were Saturday classes still being held?
Yes.
Okay.
I didn't have too many Saturday, but we did have Saturday classes.
And your major was math?
My major is mathematics.
Describe enrolling that first semester.
Did you stand in line over at...
Stood in a long line.
It took about
I would say, no exaggeration, two hours to get my classes.
I mean, just, it was, the procedures to get a course of study were very,
in my opinion, it was almost like harassment.
It wasn't very organized.
I had to go to too many different places to get a class schedule.
You would have thought it would have all been done in a central location, but I had to go to several different places to enroll.
All right, describe going to class as a beginning freshman.
Going to class as a beginning freshman was a terrifying experience because on the way to that class, you would meet
you'd have to pass upperclassmen, or you would see upperclassmen that you knew, and you would have to call them by name.
And so you were always on, you know, pins and needles.
You always scouted at least a block ahead to take the path of least,
least resistance, obviously, to get to the course on time, but to avoid where people were because then you'd have to say hello to those upperclassmen.
And you were living in which dorm area?
I was living in the core area in dorm six my first year, and then in dorm four my second year, and then I went to core staff my last two years, dorm two.
That first semester, did you have any courses that ended up being important to you later?
Describe those and why.
The first, the most important one that I took that first year was I was in the honors program and I took a course on great books and the great books of the world and it was in that course
that I met a lot of my current friends, people like Wayne Prescott and Kent Caperton, Mark Caperton, excuse me, Mark Caperton, Kent's brother.
They were in that class, and it was the one class where I met a lot of the leadership of the civilian student body, and that course shaped a lot of my thinking
for how I was going to act in later years at A&M.
I didn't realize it at the time, but those people that were in that class as freshmen, for some reason, I guess people in the honors program tend to be leaders.
They were the leaders on the civilian side of... Was the instructor in that honors course important?
His name was Dr. Abbott, and I'll never forget.
John Paul Abbott.
Make believe I didn't know him.
Describe him.
He was a, to me, if I were going to draw a professor,
you know, close my eyes and draw a professor, I would draw him like Dr. Abbott.
He was, you know, he had glasses and he had beautiful white hair.
When he spoke to you, his glasses would go down on his nose and he'd peer and look at you over those glasses.
He was a very kind and gentle man, yet very

uh i mean in his disposition but extremely demanding and what he expected you to produce as far as analysis of the books i remember studying job with him the book of job was one of the books we studied and the way the way he taught that book
was completely different than anything I'd ever learned in a Catholic church.
And so he was, he made a great, great impression.
That was Dr. Skravanek.

was another one because I decided to minor in Russian in college because I already knew Spanish and I wanted to learn another language and this was again during the Cold War and I thought why not know, why not get to know the language of the enemy and so I decided to learn Russian and I was very good at Russian.
I had a straight, I had a 4.0 grade point in Russian.
I never made anything less than an A and I
If I'd taken like six more hours, I think I would have had a double major.
I would have had a major in Russian as well.
What about your first math courses since that was your major?
First math courses were, you know, advanced algebra and calculus.
I took a lot of math courses, and I did very great in math until I got to the theory.
I was better in the application portions and the formula portions of math than I was in the proving theorems and getting into the deep analysis of differential equations, you know.
What were your personal guidelines about going to class, behavior, study, and all that?
My freshman and sophomore year was to maximize my grades, to get the best grades I possibly could.
Did you go every day to class?
I never missed a class that I can... Where did you sit?
I always sat in the back of the room on the right-hand side.
Why?

so I could observe what was going on in front of me and know what, to this day, when I go into a hearing, I sit in the very back of the room so I can observe everything that's going on, who's there, who's paying attention, who's not paying attention, and also be close to the exit.
Did you ever go to sleep in class?
I can't, never, never that I can recall.
I was tired, I'm sure, but I can't ever recall falling asleep in class.
And you and your buddies, what were your study routines?
My study routines were in between classes,
Haskell, I would go to library, and I had a, you know, I'd go to the stacks and hide, so nobody would see me, and I'd avoid upperclassmen, and so I would find a quiet place in the library to study.
Where was your special place?
I used to go to, like, the fourth floor, fourth, fourth stacks, where I, you know, close to a window, you know, so I could look out, and, but, but very few people went up there, I mean, but.
And nobody was bothered in the library, were they?
Nobody bothered me in the library.
Where were the other interference-free areas?
The only other interference-free area that I found was in the men's restroom where there were lots of stalls and you could shut the stall and study in there and nobody would

would bother you and so I I'd find a restroom and I'd sit there sometimes for 30 minutes reading a book or sounds crazy but I knew that with that door shut nobody nobody would bother me it was quiet now in the MSC y'all weren't hazed though were you we weren't hazing the MSC but there was there was there was too much activity and too much distraction I'd also go to the
At night, I used to go to the Bermuda Inn and get a cup of coffee and sometimes spend an hour there.
How would you get over there?
I'm now advancing to the end of my sophomore year.
Junior year, I got a car and I would drive there.
But your freshman year, you didn't have wheels?
No.
Let's see.
In your freshman year, where did you and your buddies play, relax?
The main place that we would relax would be at the MSC.
That pretty much was, or we'd relax by going running anywhere but the quadrangle area.
So we'd go run.
On the campus though?
On the campus and other parts of the campus.
You know where that golf course was?
The golf course was there.
What did you wear when you ran?
Shorts?
Shorts, yes.
We always, our outfit had certain color shorts and we'd wear those shorts and wear that and a t-shirt and we'd take off the t-shirt if it was too warm.
In your freshman year or so, was there anybody to whom you turned for academic advice?
Not in my outfit, there was not.
No, but I mean any teacher, advisor, assistant dean?
No.
How soon was it before you got involved in some pranks, some good bull, some
Immediately.
I mean, you know, as a class we were always trying to harass the upperclassmen.
Give some examples of fish pranks.

One of the fish pranks that, one example would be is that those of us that had a car, and I didn't have one my freshman year as mentioned earlier, but we'd go out into the country and we'd find chickens.

or we'd find a rooster and we would know when an upperclassman was going home to spend time with his family on a weekend or go see his girlfriend so we'd find a way to get that chicken or that rooster into that individual's closet and we'd lock that chicken or that rooster in the closet and after three days it was not a pretty sight.
Uniform-wise or otherwise.
Or if anybody had the unfortunate...
I remember one time I ran over an armadillo and we put that armadillo in a paper sack.
We brought him back and we found the softest pillow we could in an upperclassman's room.
And put that armadillo to bed.
In the pillow?
In the bed, covered up on the pillow.
And...
Normally, what was the response of the person who had the prank played on them?
What did they do?
Well, they obviously would try to find who the...
you know, who the instigator was, and it was always me, sir, or I did it, sir.
Even though you may not have done it, it may have been your freshman buddies down the hall or upstairs, but we were, you know, all one, and we were always guilty.
What was then the punishment?
then the most horrible punishment was having to go to the community showers in our rain gear and which was heavy heavy rubber and in our

heavy boots and having to do push-ups and sit-ups until you could hardly stand it and while while there was steam you know coming from the showers they put the showers on hot and and so the combination of steam
